fields.description:
There are currently 3 timeout handlers which are created in {{com.eucalyptus.ws.Handlers#channelMonitors}}:
# ReadTimeOutHandler [1]: Triggers a {{ReadTimeoutException}} when {{timeout}} has elaspsed without a read.
# IdleStateHandler [2]: Triggers a channel {{IdleStateEvent}} when {{timeout}} has elaspsed without a read, write, or both (depending on parameters).
# WriteTimeOutHandler [3]: Triggers a {{WriteTimeoutException}} when {{timeout}} has elaspsed without a write.

These timeout handlers need to be used in two scenarios:  web services server socket and internal client request socket.  The important bit is that there are two message exchange patterns (request & response, streaming) which need to be sensibly handled by the timeout.

Currently:  Having both the {{ReadTimeoutHandler}} and the {{WriteTimeoutHandler}} would result in a timeout when either a read or a write hadn't happened for {{timeout}}.  

Instead, what is needed is a timeout exception which is triggered when both a read and a write haven't happened for {{timeout}}.

This means a change like:
*/com/eucalyptus/ws/Handlers.java:247*
{code}
  public static Map<String, ChannelHandler> channelMonitors( final TimeUnit unit, final int timeout ) {
    return new HashMap<String, ChannelHandler>( 2 ) {
      {
        this.put( "idlehandler", new IdleStateHandler( Handlers.timer, 0, 0, timeout, unit ) );
        this.put( "idlecloser", new IdleStateAwareChannelHandler() {

          @Override
          public void channelIdle( ChannelHandlerContext ctx, IdleStateEvent e ) {
            if ( e.getState() == IdleState.ALL_IDLE ) {
              e.getChannel().close();
            }
          }

        } );
      }
    };
  }
{code}

This leaves only the {{IdleStateHandler}} on both the server and client sockets.  The resulting behaviour will be to trigger when either:
# A user or the system has not sent any data for {{timeout}}
# The system has not received a remote response for {{timeout}}

[1] http://docs.jboss.org/netty/3.2/api/org/jboss/netty/handler/timeout/ReadTimeoutHandler.html
[2] http://docs.jboss.org/netty/3.2/api/org/jboss/netty/handler/timeout/IdleStateHandler.html
[3] http://docs.jboss.org/netty/3.2/api/org/jboss/netty/handler/timeout/WriteTimeoutHandler.html
